stage-0.body:
MCP (Model Context Protocol) is how Claude Code talks to tools and data outside itself ŌĆö a GitHub server, a database, an internal API, the codebase knowledge graph this very project uses. **Project-scoped** servers are declared in **`.mcp.json`** at the project root (committed, team-shared). **User-** and **local-scoped** servers live in `~/.claude.json` in your home directory ŌĆö note that MCP's "local" scope is *not* a file in the repo, unlike `settings.local.json`.

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "github": {
      "command": "/usr/local/bin/github-mcp-server",
      "env": { "GITHUB_TOKEN": "${GITHUB_TOKEN}" }
    },
    "filesystem": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "/srv/allowed-dir"]
    }
  }
}
```

### The three scopes (per the docs)

| Scope | Available in | Shared via VCS | Stored in |
|-------|--------------|----------------|-----------|
| Local (default) | Current project only | No | `~/.claude.json` |
| Project | Current project only | **Yes** | `.mcp.json` in project root |
| User | All your projects | No | `~/.claude.json` |

### Notes that bite people

- **Secrets via `${VAR}` interpolation, never literals.** Claude Code supports `${VAR}` and `${VAR:-default}` expansion in `.mcp.json`. Since the file is committed, put `${GITHUB_TOKEN}` in the file and the real token in the environment. A token pasted into `.mcp.json` is a token pushed to the remote.
- **Project `.mcp.json` is shared; trust is gated.** The docs: *"For security reasons, Claude Code prompts for approval before using project-scoped servers from `.mcp.json` files."* Reset choices with `claude mcp reset-project-choices`. Review what a repo wants to run before approving ŌĆö a committed MCP server is executable config arriving from the repo.
- **MCP is a presentation layer, not a requirement.** Per this ecosystem's tooling policy, prefer importing shared Python libraries directly in orchestration code; reach for MCP when an *interactive* agent needs to discover and choose tools mid-conversation. Don't bolt on a large always-on MCP surface just because you can.

The payoff for the stage-0 thesis: declare a server in `.mcp.json`, commit it, and it's available identically in every front-end ŌĆö the GUI doesn't have its own separate tool list. (Sources: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/mcp, https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings)

stage-2.body:
`.claude/settings.json` is where the *enforceable* configuration lives ŌĆö the part that, unlike `CLAUDE.md`, does not depend on the model deciding to cooperate. It has three load-bearing sections.

```json
{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json",
  "permissions": {
    "allow": ["Bash(npm run test:*)", "Bash(npm run lint)"],
    "ask":   ["Bash(git push:*)"],
    "deny":  ["Read(./.env)", "Read(.env)", "Bash(curl:*)"]
  },
  "env": {
    "NODE_ENV": "test"
  },
  "hooks": {
    "PreToolUse": [
      { "matcher": "Edit", "hooks": [{ "type": "command", "command": ".claude/hooks/protect.sh" }] }
    ]
  }
}
```

- **`permissions`** ŌĆö the allow/ask/deny rules controlling which tools the agent may use and which files/domains it may touch. The detail of how these evaluate is the next section; it's the most consequential and most misunderstood part.
- **`env`** ŌĆö environment variables injected into the session. Use this for things every teammate's agent needs set identically (telemetry flags, a test-mode env). Don't put secrets here ŌĆö `settings.json` is committed.
- **`hooks`** ŌĆö shell commands fired at lifecycle events (e.g. `PreToolUse`, `SessionStart`). Hooks are the *enforcement* layer: a `PreToolUse` hook that exits with code 2 "stops the tool call before permission rules are evaluated," so the block applies even when an allow rule would otherwise let the call through. This is how you make "never edit `migrations/` directly" a hard wall instead of a hope. (Most settings hot-reload ŌĆö the docs note `permissions`, `hooks`, and credential helpers reload without a restart; `model` and `outputStyle` are read once at session start.)

### Why both CLAUDE.md and settings.json
They're complementary, and the docs draw the line sharply in a table: use **CLAUDE.md for behavioral guidance** ("Code style and quality guidelines") and **managed/settings for technical enforcement** ("Block specific tools, commands, or file paths"). `CLAUDE.md` asks; `settings.json` deny-rules and hooks *enforce*. If you find yourself writing "NEVER push to main" in `CLAUDE.md` and hoping, you want an `ask`/`deny` rule like `Bash(git push origin main)` or a `PreToolUse` hook instead.

stage-3.body:
Here is the single most important distinction in this stage. `CLAUDE.md` is **advisory** ŌĆö the model reads it and *usually* complies, but under load or distraction it can drift. A **hook** is a command (or other handler) that runs on a lifecycle event and **fires no matter what the model decides** (code.claude.com/docs/en/hooks). If a rule must be true 100% of the time, it is a hook, not a sentence in a markdown file. Hooks fire deterministically on event + matcher conditions and can hard-block.

### Configuration shape (settings.json)

```json
{
  "hooks": {
    "PreToolUse": [
      {
        "matcher": "Bash",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "if": "Bash(git push --force *)",
            "command": "${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/.claude/hooks/block-force-push.sh",
            "timeout": 10
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

Three nesting levels: `EventName` ŌåÆ `matcher` (which tool/source) ŌåÆ `hooks[]` (the handlers). Settings locations, in resolution order **managed policy ŌåÆ project ŌåÆ local ŌåÆ user ŌåÆ plugin ŌåÆ skill/agent**: `~/.claude/settings.json` (user), `.claude/settings.json` (shareable, checked in), `.claude/settings.local.json` (gitignored), plugin `hooks/hooks.json`, or skill/agent frontmatter.

### Matchers and the `if` field

For tool events the matcher is the tool name: `"Bash"`, `"Edit|Write"` (pipe-separated list), or a JS regex like `"mcp__github__.*"`. `"*"`, `""`, or omitting it matches all. MCP tools follow `mcp__<server>__<tool>`. Non-tool events match other things ŌĆö `SessionStart` matches `startup`/`resume`/`clear`/`compact`; `SubagentStart` matches the agent type. The per-handler **`if`** field narrows further using permission-rule syntax (`"Bash(rm *)"`, `"Edit(*.ts)"`); it strips leading `VAR=value` assignments and inspects `$()`/backtick subcommands, and is only evaluated on tool events.

### How a hook hard-blocks

Two mechanisms. **Exit code 2** blocks the action and feeds stderr back to Claude. Or, on exit 0, emit structured JSON:

```bash
#!/bin/bash
COMMAND=$(jq -r '.tool_input.command')
if echo "$COMMAND" | grep -qE 'push .*(--force|-f)\b'; then
  jq -n '{
    hookSpecificOutput: {
      hookEventName: "PreToolUse",
      permissionDecision: "deny",
      permissionDecisionReason: "Force-push to remote is blocked by policy."
    }
  }'
else
  exit 0   # no decision; normal permission flow applies
fi
```

| Exit code | Meaning |
|-----------|---------|
| `0` | Success. stdout parsed for JSON control output. |
| `2` | **Blocking error.** stderr fed to Claude; action blocked. JSON ignored. |
| other | Non-blocking error. stderr shown to user; execution continues. |

Note that conventional Unix `exit 1` is *non-blocking* here ŌĆö only `2` blocks. The `PreToolUse` `permissionDecision` accepts `allow|deny|ask|defer`, and can even rewrite the call via `updatedInput`. Top-level-decision events (`UserPromptSubmit`, `Stop`, `PostToolBatch`) use `{"decision": "block", "reason": "..."}` instead.

stage-4.body:
Telling every new hire to run two `/plugin` commands is the manual-coordination failure mode all over again. Push the marketplace and the default plugin set into the repo's `.claude/settings.json` so trusting the project folder is enough.

```json
{
  "extraKnownMarketplaces": {
    "acme-tools": {
      "source": { "source": "github", "repo": "acme/claude-plugins" },
      "autoUpdate": true
    }
  },
  "enabledPlugins": {
    "code-review@acme-tools": true,
    "deploy-tools@acme-tools": true
  }
}
```

When a teammate trusts the repository folder, Claude Code prompts them to install these marketplaces and plugins. `extraKnownMarketplaces` *registers* the catalog; `enabledPlugins` says which plugins should be on by default. `autoUpdate: true` (admin-settable per entry) keeps the org marketplace current without each person toggling it. Note the defaults: official Anthropic marketplaces auto-update; third-party and local-dev marketplaces do **not** unless you opt in.

### CLI declares scope, too

```bash
claude plugin marketplace add acme/claude-plugins --scope project
claude plugin install code-review@acme-tools --scope project
```

Scopes: **user** (you, everywhere ŌĆö the install default), **project** (shared via `.claude/settings.json`), **local** (you, this repo only). For a team shelf you want **project** scope so the config is committed and shared. You may also see **managed** scope ŌĆö admin-installed via managed settings, not user-modifiable.

### Locking it down (managed settings)

Administrators can restrict which marketplaces anyone may add via `strictKnownMarketplaces` in **managed** settings (which users and project config cannot override):

```json
{
  "strictKnownMarketplaces": [
    { "source": "github", "repo": "acme/approved-plugins" },
    { "source": "hostPattern", "hostPattern": "^github\\.acme\\.com$" }
  ]
}
```

`[]` = total lockdown (no new marketplaces); a list = allowlist only; undefined = no restriction. Source types include exact `github`/`url`, plus regex `hostPattern` and `pathPattern`. Pair it with `extraKnownMarketplaces` so the approved catalog is also auto-registered (`strictKnownMarketplaces` restricts but does not register). For CI/containers, `CLAUDE_CODE_PLUGIN_SEED_DIR` pre-populates plugins at image-build time so nothing clones at runtime (the seed is read-only and its entries take precedence).

The mitigation is not "don't use plugins" ŌĆö it's to treat a plugin like any other dependency you'd pull into your build, and to put the team shelf where you control it.

### Pre-install review (the non-negotiable)

Before anyone clicks Trust, **read the code**: `plugin.json`, every `SKILL.md`, `hooks/hooks.json`, and any MCP server implementation. The **Will install** pane and `claude plugin details` enumerate every component ŌĆö use them. Hooks and MCP servers deserve the hardest look because they're where arbitrary execution lives. The **Context cost** line in the same pane is a second signal: a "review skill" that wants to add thousands of tokens per turn is worth a second look.

### Minimize the trust radius

Prefer the smallest primitive that does the job: a plain skill over a full plugin, a local script over a remote MCP server, where feasible. Smaller surface, smaller blast radius. `defaultEnabled: false` on a marketplace entry lets you ship something installed-but-off until a user deliberately opts in.

### Pin to reviewed commits

Use `sha` pins in the marketplace's plugin `source` so everyone runs exactly the bytes you audited. An unpinned git source means "every push is auto-deployed to the team" ŌĆö fine for your own actively-developed plugins, dangerous for anything you didn't write.

### Run a private, allowlisted marketplace

Host the team marketplace in a **private** GitHub repo (the docs and researchers both recommend this over public distribution; Claude Code installs from private repos using your existing git credential helpers). Then close the door with managed settings:

```json
{
  "strictKnownMarketplaces": [
    { "source": "github", "repo": "acme/approved-plugins" }
  ],
  "extraKnownMarketplaces": {
    "approved-plugins": { "source": { "source": "github", "repo": "acme/approved-plugins" } }
  }
}
```

Now the only shelf anyone can pull from is the one you review. The docs are explicit that `strictKnownMarketplaces` is checked *before* any network or filesystem operation, on add **and** on every install/update/refresh/auto-update, and it cannot be overridden by user or project settings. Note one matching gotcha: it uses **exact** matching (a trailing slash, `.git` suffix, or `ssh://` vs `https://` are different values), so prefer a `hostPattern` entry over a literal URL when a repo can be cloned by more than one URL form.

stage-6.body:
Discovery is good, but you don't want onboarding to depend on each engineer remembering to run `/plugin marketplace add`. You make the marketplace **part of the repo** so that trusting the project folder prompts installation automatically ([Marketplaces ŌåÆ Require for your team](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/plugin-marketplaces)).

This is the bridge between Tier 1 and Tier 2: the marketplace *lives* in Tier 2, but the *declaration that this repo uses it* is committed Tier-1 project config in `.claude/settings.json`:

```json
// .claude/settings.json  (committed)
{
  "extraKnownMarketplaces": {
    "acme-tools": {
      "source": { "source": "github", "repo": "acme-corp/claude-plugins" }
    }
  },
  "enabledPlugins": {
    "quality-tools@acme-tools": true,
    "deploy-tools@acme-tools": true
  }
}
```

Now a new hire clones the repo, trusts the folder, and Claude Code prompts them to install exactly the plugins the team relies on. `enabledPlugins` decides which are on by default.

### Gotcha: marketplace state is per-user, not per-project

Marketplace registrations live once per user in `~/.claude/plugins/known_marketplaces.json`, and each plugin is copied into a versioned cache under `~/.claude/plugins/cache`. Consequences:

- A plugin **cannot** reference files outside its own directory (no `../shared-utils`) ŌĆö they aren't copied. Use `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}` for in-plugin paths, or symlinks for genuinely shared assets.
- For containers/CI, pre-seed with `CLAUDE_CODE_PLUGIN_SEED_DIR`. Build the seed once (run Claude Code, install the plugins, copy `~/.claude/plugins`), then point the variable at it. The seed mirrors `~/.claude/plugins`:

```text
$CLAUDE_CODE_PLUGIN_SEED_DIR/
  known_marketplaces.json
  marketplaces/<name>/...
  cache/<marketplace>/<plugin>/<version>/...
```

The seed is **read-only** (auto-updates are disabled for it) and its entries take precedence over the user's config on each startup, so the image starts fully provisioned and clones nothing at runtime.
